President Muhammadu Buhari has signed the new minimum wage bill. The bill, which has now become a law, will usher in a new pay structure for Nigerian workers. The National Assembly had passed the bill approving N30,000 as the minimum wage for workers. State governors had opposed the N30,000 minimum wage with many of them saying they will be unable to pay their workers. Details later… The National Council of State (NCS) yesterday approved N27,000 as the New National Minimum Wage of workers in the country. The Council is presided over by President Muhammadu Buhari as chairman while Vice President Yemi Osinbajo is vice chairman. Other members of NCS are state governors, all former heads of… In “News” Barely one month after the Senate endorsed the National Minimum Wage Bill, organised labour, under the aegis of Trade Union Side (TUS) of the Joint National Public Service Negotiating Council (JNPSNC), has enjoined President Muhammadu Buhari to sign the N30,000 minimum wage into law to put smiles on the faces… In “Business” As organised labour moves to call out Nigerians for another industrial action in a few days over governments positions, both at states and federal levels, on the proposed new minimum wage, it is better to forestall it to prevent more problems on the economy and the tensed political atmosphere. Sunday… In “Business”